column1: 195010;instagram;2019-01-29 12:15:23;FALSE;"***story alert 🚨 *** so yesterday evening i was feeling a bit low
column2: it can often be like that post gig - (highs & lows) however i decided to kick myself up the butt & go for a cycle in the rain to collect my @ctmfestival pass. en route i was listening to 90’s dnb & starting to feel hyped. remembering how i used to walk around with clash of the titans tape packs that my mate would bring me all the way from ldn
column3: and how it helped me outrun the kids that chased me & tried to beat me up

column2: saw that it got me into the other shows & into the lectures at transmediale the following week - yessss! i checked out some awesome art & felt inspired again. i cycled home with my dnb soundtrack & thought about this year’s ctm theme ‘persistence’ and how ctm is 20 yo. i’ve been djing now for 18 years and there have been stages in my life where i gave up
column3: but somehow the music kept finding me again. about how i had a record label & lived on oats & brown rice or whatever my studio mates could donate me so my partner @maihyper and i could press to vinyl. after the 3rd release we ran out of cash & just couldn’t bring ourselves to only release digitally. we were satisfied with what we had done & left it that. by the next year we had licensed 2 of our tracks to @warprecords & @houndstoothlbl & managed to break even. 🙌🏾 ✨. #persistence ~ i started out in the bass music scene & found myself hitting so many f**kin glass ceilings it hurt
column5: blamed it on my freaky & wild personality. i encountered a ridiculous amount of coercive & non consensual incidents - honestly too many to count
column6: always hungry to have my music heard & to be listened to
column7: i walked into many shit situations. here comes my #metoo (that’s been a long time coming) to quote my clever friend @spiritualdaddyexperience ‘i am not posting for pity and my trauma is not a lemonade stand’ this is a statement about #persistence & solidarity for my 🏳️‍🌈 family & for my poc friends. (having learned of my white privilege) i’m very thankful for my @lllecken family - who have breathed life back into my soul. plz msg me if u r struggling & need strong words ❤️";;en;#persistence

column1: 195072;instagram;2019-01-29 13:29:16;FALSE;"‎واستمعت النيابة لأقوال والدة التلميذة مقدمة الشكوى والتي أفادت أنه حال عودة نجلتها التلميذة بالصف الثالث الابتدائي للمنزل عقب انتهاء اليوم الدراسي، وجدتها في حالة رعب وخوف شديد، وبسؤالها عن سبب ذلك قررت أن المتهم – مدرس اللغة العربية بالمدرسة – قام باستدعائها داخل أحد الفصول الخالية بالمدرسة وقام بالإمساك بها عنوة والقيام بالعديد من الأفعال والملامسات الجسدية كنوع من التحرش الجنسي و الانتهاك الجسدي لها، ولم ينقذها إلا أن عدد من زميلاتها شاهدنها من شباك الفصل وسارعت إحداهن بفتح باب الفصل لتبلغ الجاني بأن مدير المدرسة يطلب حضور التلميذة -المجني عليها- حتى تتمكن من اصطحابها ومغادرة الفصل.

column1: 195097;instagram;2019-01-29 14:02:50;FALSE;"today i’m grateful for our old neighborhood facebook feed
column2: before it was purged and fascistically nicewashed. there
column3: i learned that i wasn’t alone in wishing dogs would be leashed in our local bird sanctuary
column4: that i wasn’t the only one who didn’t love our local fatphobic nurse practitioner
column5: that people will argue for like a million comments about street harassment
column7: the dry cleaner on our block is a jerk
column9: etc. i found great comfort in watching the notifications roll in as people got fired up and hashed things out. or didn’t.

column2: dogs. people have looked at me like i’m a monster because i didn’t immediately embrace the affections of their dog
column3: and thanks to the awesome old feed i know it’s not just me.

column1: as a trauma survivor with mild ptsd
column2: one of the hardest things to manage is the social expectation that i cheerfully accept unwanted touch. it’s messed up
column5: and it keeps happening in carpenter’s woods.

column3: shouted “i don’t care!” at the lady. that’s why i’m still on this. this watercolor is for that lady

column1: 195119;instagram;2019-01-29 14:10:26;FALSE;"former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel
column2: but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

column1: in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23
column2: flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia
column3: and kushner spoke with kim darroch
column4: the british ambassador to the united states
column5: according to diplomats familiar with the conversations
column6: who spoke on condition of anonymity.

column1: the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump
column2: who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric
column3: took office on jan. 20. it failed
column4: with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

column1: the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move
column2: egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution
column3: prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

column1: a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a ""high level"" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.
according to court documents made public on friday
column2: a member of trump's presidential transition team
column3: later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner
column4: told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments
column6: to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

column1: flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day

195128;instagram;2019-01-29 14:37:55;FALSE;i just finished the ted bundy tapes thing and i need to tell you my thoughts. 🚨violent trigger warning: i’m going to say some very upsetting things about him ahead🚨bundy brutally murdered upwards of 30 women (some say the number is closer to 100). he returned to the site where he disposed these women to pose them, dress them up, apply makeup to them, and have sex with their decomposing bodies until they became completely putrefied. he severed the heads of women and kept them as trophies in his home and disposed them later. he incinerated the heads of women in his girlfriend’s fireplace. he used a fake disability to lure his victims to his car where he would then bash them over the head, handcuff them and brutally murder them. the documentary didn’t cover any of this. instead it showed his “fans”...girls in the trial excited by being so close to a serial woman killer. the documentary mentioned how handsome he was maybe 78 times. they painted him as a handsome man who could have been a great attorney but instead woopsies violently murdered and sexually assaulted women! the director of this documentary is also the man at the helm of the movie where zac efron plays bundy. i think he did this so he can sell tickets to his film. instead of making a movie about a monster he made a movie about a sexy guy who was into really, really rough sex! the trailer looks like a mash up of american hustle and wolf of wall street. the music makes it sound like it’s a zippy rom com with a kooky twist! not only is it disrespectful to the victims and their families it’s also just kinda...why? what is the point of this film? there’s some strange uptick in sexual violence in the media. glamorizing stalking (“you”), sexualizing serial killers (bundy) is sending a very weird, confusing message in a post #metoo world. would love to hear your thoughts about the doc and the sexualization of violence in media today! thanks for coming to my tedbundytalks™️! column1: 195161;instagram;2019-01-29 15:10:30;FALSE;"i spent last evening listening to tarana burke speak as part of tuskegee university’s lyceum series. her talk about how the me too movement began
column3: and where it’s going had me sitting on the edge of my seat. i do not share the experiences of those who can identify with the hashtag metoo
column4: but i hurt so deeply for anyone who has been hurt or violated in any manner. i have students who have shared their experiences with me and i was not equipped to even began to help them. afraid of saying the wrong thing...i would promptly alert someone who had the knowledge and resources to help them. ❤️ i learned a lot last night
column5: one thing is that sharing your story and healing are two different things! 🤔 healing doesn’t end with sharing. it’s a delicate process to say the least.

column1: she discussed the r kelly documentary (i couldn’t watch it but i think that i will now for the purpose of understanding)
column2: how hollywood has embraced (or misused) the movement and how she’s been viewed in the media and social media. accused of “bringing down black men”
column4: “i can love and uplift black women while loving and holding black men accountable “ 👏🏾👏🏾👏🏾 any time you get the opportunity to hear tarana speak please indulge yourself. she’s real and raw and passionate and compassionate... her photo will take center place on the shirt of my afro wearing girl who will adorn my classroom door during the month of february! it was a pleasure to meet you again @taranajaneen  thank you mrs. norma jackson for the invite!

column1: i realize where i’ve failed myself. i see now how i’ve silenced my voice out of shame and guilt. —

column2: i was violated by someone who i had known from school for years. —

column1: the thing is i didn’t speak up. i didn’t cry out for help. i was almost scared of being heard. —
i made a choice to go to a place where i had no business being there. i was with someone i had no business spending time with. —
maybe i wanted to be cool. maybe i wanted to feel included. —
i made a bad choice in going and in not speaking up. —
but he is responsible for his own actions. —

column2: i have been ashamed of my story. whenever there are spaces calling for love and solidarity among those affected by sexual assault
column3: i have hesitated in putting my hand up and saying #metoo —

column2: but i could have done more. i could have screamed. i could have said something the next day or the next or the next. as time went on it got harder to find the will to say anything at all. —

column1: i was scared no one would believe me or that the focus of blame would be on me. —
i take responsibility for my actions. i do not take responsibility for his. —

column3: i have not felt entirely safe in my body. eight years later
column4: i am still uncovering wounds to heal. —

column5: aggression at strangers and those i love. i did not know why. —

column1: i have been scared that i wouldn’t be able to protect myself. —

column2: i’m talking to myself. i’m apologizing to myself. forgiving myself. reminding myself i am safe and i am capable of protecting myself in my everyday. —

column1: finally someone acknowledging what really happens in kitchens
column2: one of the harshest environments for a woman to work in. having spent 11 years in the industry i have witnessed first hand and personally experienced physical
column4: emotional and sexual abuse by “some” male chefs in restaurants. an industry that wants to make you feel small from day one until you have proven yourself! with whatever that may entail. with horrific hours and appalling pay it’s no wonder women don’t want to work in kitchens. .

column1: over the last few years i have had the absolute pleasure to work in female focussed kitchens with incredible men. the dynamic needs to change! strength shouldn’t need to come from enduring abuse
column2: but instead from within a supportive and creative environment. cooking is an incredible passion
column3: working in a kitchen is a thrill that i still get. let’s strive to make kitchens a safe place for young ambitious women to work in. allow them to aspire to their goals without the obstacle of abuse and harassment. ❤️💪🏼❤️ @herrickkitchen @vikulaif @knay7 @thedetoxkitchen @ellagalt @whereareyoutapatio @bauhoffer_ @lapetrella @monosydemas @albertozanrosso @anevalenciano @metoomvmt #feminist #cheflife #metoo #girlpower #veganchef #healthylifestyle #change #passion #ambition #future #dreams #equality #restaurantlife #healthyfood #vegansofspain";;en;#feminist

column1: 195226;instagram;2019-01-29 16:42:53;FALSE;happy 3rd birthday to “1954” this song changed my life for so many reasons! i am so grateful for the immense support it received and still does!! thank you @thebeat925 to be the first in canada to support it on commercial radio! a massive thank you to @popjustice who premiered the song! then brian in australia also took a chance on it followed by rob at hot radio uk...then @zara ended up playing this track in all their stores worldwide! and it’s still heard in zara and mcdonald’s today!! 🤯 the amount of messages i received about 1954 was incredible. i was humbled (and still am) that it touched so many people and made them feel like they could fight harder for who they are because of it. sadly
column2: the message of this song rings truer today than it did 3 years ago when i wrote it. but we all move forward together in positivity and resolute defiance
column3: and in our high heels of course 😜❤️ a massive massive thank you to the music team behind this! @exeter_sound_studios who produced and co- wrote this with me. dan miller for his genius programming
column5: and to @lacquer_channel_phil & tom coyne (rip) for the incredible master. to @sethnm who directed this video and supported and championed a video that pushed the boundaries. to @mistyfox & @the_shannon_leigh for the insane hair and make up job that day!! and to all my friends who took part that day as extras 💓 this song holds such a special part in my heart because this is real life. this is how i truly felt. and when you tell the truth

column1: 195236;instagram;2019-01-29 16:47:39;FALSE;"every now and then i suffer from a traumatic memory of my sexual abuse. rather it's in the form of a nightmare or if i""m living my day-to-day and am triggered by something.

column2: if i had a choice i would choose to forget the painful childhood memories of abuse. i'd choose to only remember the good things about my childhood.

column1: but our brain isn't wired that way. we store memories
when flashbacks of my past resurface
1- how i'm forever impacted by my sexual abuse trauma.
2- how the lord has healed me from so many things relating to my sexual abuse.
3-that i will never forget what has happened to me.
although the memories of abuse are sketched into my brain

column1: 195244;instagram;2019-01-29 17:05:05;FALSE;"representation matters. in everything. including in the depiction of domestic trafficking victims and survivors and our experiences - which are myriad
column2: varied and rarely bear much resemblance to the media portrayals of what trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation looks like. these sensationalized images - overwhelmingly and almost exclusively representing one type of victim - white
column5: blonde - and one type of experience - kidnapped
column8: ‘duct taped’ - are harmful. at gems we’ve seen the damage that they do for years as victims who don’t look like this and whose experiences are more complex than this are viewed and treated as less deserving of empathy or services
column9: as somehow culpable in their own victimization. those manufactured images get lodged in people’s minds as the dominant
column11: narrative and leads to real life victims of commercial sexual exploitation and trafficking being ignored
column13: or even criminalized. this narrative has created an environment where erroneous claims about women being duct taped and brought across the border in windowless vans en masse are believed and used as a justification for harmful policies. it’s not just movies and tv though
column14: much of the anti-trafficking movement bears responsibility for misleading and biased ‘awareness’ materials and using the most sensational images and the most ‘sympathetic’ version of a victim to reach the public. it may get people’s attention initially but in the long term it only does more harm. join survivors at gems as we say #representationmatterstosurvivors and push back against this narrative. please share this video and advocate for a broader
column15: more inclusive and more accurate depiction of domestic trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation. .

column1: 195263;instagram;2019-01-29 17:35:46;FALSE;"check my story tho..vote on my poll if you would 💖 also ☢️tw ahead☢️ in regards to this post i used to do this so much in high school. i'm 21 now but when i was 15-17 i had this boyfriend named ""a"". he was one of those burn out druggy boys but damn was he cute and damn did he make me feel so special. turns out he made a lot of girls feel special while we were together. but anyway
column5: etc. and although i was  already shing i got into stealing
column6: dangerous drugs (surprisingly i didn't even smoke weed..i mean i do that now but weed is different j.s. j.s. j.s. fight me) and making myself more promiscuous to please him. this turned into me doing whatever he told me to do and i lost all of my friends
column7: my family didn't talk to me for months unless they were restricting me in my grounding even more
column9: i was arrested multiple times (no charges thank god) and i slipped up my grades from a 4.23 gpa down to barely passing with a 2.1 gpa. i turned my life around after the fifth time he went to juvi but if i didn't have the will power like some high school girls struggle with
column10: idk where i'd be now just because i changed myself just to convince myself that the cute boy i was dating would stop abusing me sexually
column13: still love me and be with me. don't change yourself. don't lose sight of your values for someone else. stay strong and remember your self worth. xx

column1: representation matters. in everything. including in the depiction of domestic trafficking victims and survivors and our experiences - which are myriad
column2: varied and rarely bear much resemblance to the media portrayals of what trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation looks like. these sensationalized images - overwhelmingly and almost exclusively representing one type of victim - white
column5: blonde - and one type of experience - kidnapped
column8: ‘duct taped’ - are harmful. at gems we’ve seen the damage that they do for years as victims who don’t look like this and whose experiences are more complex than this are viewed and treated as less deserving of empathy or services
column9: as somehow culpable in their own victimization. those manufactured images get lodged in people’s minds as the dominant
column11: narrative and leads to real life victims of commercial sexual exploitation and trafficking being ignored
column13: or even criminalized. this narrative has created an environment where erroneous claims about women being duct taped and brought across the border in windowless vans en masse are believed and used as a justification for harmful policies. it’s not just movies and tv though
column14: much of the anti-trafficking movement bears responsibility for misleading and biased ‘awareness’ materials and using the most sensational images and the most ‘sympathetic’ version of a victim to reach the public. it may get people’s attention initially but in the long term it only does more harm. join survivors at gems as we say #representationmatterstosurvivors and push back against this narrative. please share this video and advocate for a broader
column15: more inclusive and more accurate depiction of domestic trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation. .

column1: i just finished the ted bundy tapes thing and i need to tell you my thoughts. 🚨violent trigger warning: i’m going to say some very upsetting things about him ahead🚨bundy brutally murdered upwards of 30 women (some say the number is closer to 100). he returned to the site where he disposed these women to pose them
column4: and have sex with their decomposing bodies until they became completely putrefied. he severed the heads of women and kept them as trophies in his home and disposed them later. he incinerated the heads of women in his girlfriend’s fireplace. he used a fake disability to lure his victims to his car where he would then bash them over the head
column5: handcuff them and brutally murder them. the documentary didn’t cover any of this. instead it showed his “fans”...girls in the trial excited by being so close to a serial woman killer. the documentary mentioned how handsome he was maybe 78 times. they painted him as a handsome man who could have been a great attorney but instead woopsies violently murdered and sexually assaulted women! the director of this documentary is also the man at the helm of the movie where zac efron plays bundy. i think he did this so he can sell tickets to his film. instead of making a movie about a monster he made a movie about a sexy guy who was into really
column6: really rough sex! the trailer looks like a mash up of american hustle and wolf of wall street. the music makes it sound like it’s a zippy rom com with a kooky twist! not only is it disrespectful to the victims and their families it’s also just kinda...why? what is the point of this film? there’s some strange uptick in sexual violence in the media. glamorizing stalking (“you”)
column7: sexualizing serial killers (bundy) is sending a very weird
column8: confusing message in a post #metoo world. would love to hear your thoughts about the doc and the sexualization of violence in media today! thanks for coming to my ted(bundy)talks™️!

column1: with the recent rise of the #metoo movement
column2: there has been increasingly more conversation about sexism in the workplace. in light of such events
column3: companies have instituted ""diversity training"" to bring awareness to gender issues and resolve discrimination.

column2: research has found that corporate “diversity training” actually makes the gender gap worse
column3: partly because it makes men feel demonized. however unintended
column4: such training divides men and women on a crucial problem that requires a coordinated effort to address.

column1: the growing disconnect between men and women stems from a lack of effective communication. while women tend to discuss these issues amongst themselves
column2: men are often unexposed to such conversations. as a result
column4: men are often left wondering how they should support women and what they should say (and not say). this uncertainty in how to behave can lead to missteps
column6: and misunderstandings that can result in real and lasting damage on women’s careers.

column3: advocates that the best way to bridge the gender gap is by bringing men into the conversation of sexism. as someone who has worked her way to the top of a male-dominated industry
column4: she has a unique perspective on how we can achieve workplace parity and why men must be mobilized to help close the gender gap.

column3: the usa today network received three pulitzer prizes
column4: including the first pulitzer in usa today's history.

column1: 195329;instagram;2019-01-29 18:35:10;FALSE;"caelynn miller-keyes one of the remaining contestants on ""the bachelor"" vying for colton underwood's love became the first to ever share her #metoo story on the show ... and it was extremely emotional.
caelynn was on a one-on-one date with colton on monday night's episode when she decided to open up ... telling him she was sexually assaulted when she was a sophomore in college in 2014
column2: after attending a frat party with 3 girlfriends.

column1: she said ... ""they drugged our wine. i woke up the next morning and i was completely naked in my bed and had no memory of the night before. and
column2: i had like a small vision of a guy in my bed
column3: and i just had this pit in my stomach like something really bad happened last night."" the former miss usa runner-up added that her friend called her the next day and told her all 3 of them were sexually assaulted by various men ... and they all got away with it except for one student who was expelled.

column2: who was crowned miss north carolina 2018
column3: opened up about being a sexual assault survivor last year ... but monday's convo with colton was the first time he learned about it.

column1: miller-keyes added the aftermath of the assault was horrible
column2: as she was initially denied a rape kit by a hospital and had to go to another one. she said the whole experience was ""so painful and it screws up every ounce of you.""

column1: caelynn is one of 13 women remaining on colton's season.

column2: an experience that had deep and lasting impact.  i have personally known the draw to watch porn.  as a broken 19-year-old
column3: i found myself trapped in the commercial sex industry
column6: emulating everything i learned about sexuality through porn.  i have also known the pain of being in a relationship with someone who was addicted to it and all of the insecurity
column7: hurt and feelings of betrayal that can cause.  and for the past 15 years
column9: i have walked alongside women as they pursue healing and freedom after working in the porn industry.

column1: i have learned that shame fuels addiction.  my heart in writing this blog is not to shame anyone
column2: but to shed light on an issue that is affecting so many.  some people still think that porn is victimless.  others even go so far as to argue that it is empowering to women.  i want people to know the truth.  i want people to be moved
column4: but to compassion and to action. •

column2: but to awaken. we cannot fix what we do long face. •

column1: 195418;instagram;2019-01-29 20:26:50;FALSE;"today i am still processing the announcement @mariannewilliamson made yesterday about running for president 2020. .
i have said this and i will say it again. we as a culture have continually used our votes based on what another says is best for us. if we choose to vote with our conscious
column2: our vote is never thrown away or wasted.

column1: whether marianne can win or not win is not the question for today. the question is
column2: can she help us take personal responsibility
column5: and shift the toxic culture of our political system for true democracy not a sociopathic economic system? .

column1: as she put it ... "" a person who has no remorse. a person who has no conscience. a person who has no ethics. a person who has no compassion is a sociopath and an economic order which does not have a conscience which does not have ethics does not compassion and which justifies its amorality by saying all our responsibility is to accrue money for a small group of people who are our stockholders that is a sociopathic economic system and that sociopathic economic system has become an economic system of tyranny in the united states of america""
as a survivor of abuse ... as a healer ... as a speaker and writer and advocate ... this is how we the people can rise up create change. .
she's calling upon us all. to not wait for someone else to do it for us. the time is now..
what if she is the #miracle? are you ready to shed your fear and take a leap of faith?
marianne williamson is the first political candidate i have ever considered volunteering for. that says a lot. .
what are you doing to help shift our political environment? .

column2: grave concerns or pity. fuck sorrys and sucks to be you’s. sympathy keeps us at arms length
column3: be sure your pain doesn’t touch me
column4: contaminate me. it isn’t even on my list of important things that you remotely begin to have your shit together.

column3: and holding space. empathy means i am willing to bear pain with you. give me me too’s and i feel you’s. i am for living the questions
column4: and embodying the process for however long it takes. it is important to me to be honest
column5: and to be willing to look.

column1: i will not stand for you as damaged goods. i do not accept you as a helpless victim. i am committed to seeing beyond circumstances. i recognize you are more

column3: so when you find yourself thrown face first into the shit

column1: . 🍀ra sheeba şifası doğrudan çakralar üzerinde çalışır. dna'mızı ve elektromanyetik alanımızı değişime uğratır. bu şekilde bize sevgi̇'yi öğretir ve onunla bağlantımızı kurar. sevgi her seviyede ilerlememize yardımcı olan şeydir. enerjiye sahip çıkmalı ve titreşimin bizi değiştirmesine izin vermeliyiz. işığa sahip çıkın. . .
• eril ve dişi enerjiyi dengeler ve güçlendirir.
• fiziksel ve ruh sal şifa verir.
• titreşimleriniz ve ruh renklerinizi değişirken sevginin benliğinizin içinden akması için yolu açar.
• dna’mızı ve elektromanyetik alanımızı değişime uğratır.
bu şekilde bize sevgi̇‘yi öğretir ve onunla bağlantımızı kurar.
• ruhtan gelen iç ses her an daha duyulur.
• zaten var olan bolluk ve bereket kendini göstermeye başlar.
• haz alış ve neşe artar. • cinsellikte doyum artar. • i̇fade rahatlığı gelir.

column3: there is a constant morphic dance of light & dark as the tao swirls & entwines within itself
column4: cycle after cycle in cosmic play of integration… its not polarity
column5: it is what it is: balance/neutrality. gaia says to me: when we disassociate ourselves from our shadows we lose our center & create fractures within our psyche/consciousness/energy field. we turn our faces to look the other way through a form of escapism
column7: weakening our cord attached to gaia’s core. we become ungrounded
column8: free radicals floating in gaia’s atmosphere. causing discord and illness. grounding is so needed not just to bring our soul in alignment with our earthly bodies
column9: but to keep gaia healthy too. to be grounded is to be accepting
column11: to be honest with ourselves. to love ourselves is to love gaia. that is why nature is so honest & healing. because when we connect to her
column12: we connect to us. how many of us are truly grounded
column13: if we ignore parts of us we find uncomfortable? how many of us are truly healed if we deny our past that brings us the lessons wrapped in experiences? kali is here now as a defender of gaia to help destroy the denials

column15: releasing the shame. there is no disconnection just disassociation. when we integrate all that we are… we transform schisms into facets like a diamond. we become crystals. made clear

column1: we are doing one or the other. there is no in-between. contribution. legacy. these ideals matter. i may not and don’t have to agree with everything or the choices of another
column2: as someone else may not and don’t have to agree with mine. but
column3: i will always believe it is the right of e-very human-being to make their own choices; for their own lives (as long as they are not inflicting harm on anyone else to do so). period. there is a disease of hate that shadows this world preventing us from elevating to our highest form. we have the power to either empower it or obliterate it. the choice has always been ours; collectively. i will say i am sorry to my fellow humans
column5: the everyday #metoo movement...i’m sorry to my fellow #abused #molested #trafficked children
column7: animals... i am sorry to the victims of this world who don’t even know (to realize) that they’re being victimized; on a daily basis. empathy. what’s my contribution
column8: my legacy to/ for this world? love. if we’re doing that
column9: there is no way hate can
column11: survive. does the state of the world reflect that? whether we like it or not
column12: we’re all in this together and we have to share this space. it’d be really sad to think/know that #koko (🦍) was and is right about us (humans). i hope you’ll continue to defy the odds loves and never give up (on yourself/or humanity). ~sophia a johnson💋🎶🎤

column1: the past few weeks i’ve been on my deathbed. i spent a week mulling over suicide
column3: and it sounds so messed up but the thought of cold water rushing into my lungs (if i lived passed the initial impact) brought a wave of relief over me.

column2: i was sexually assaulted by a “family member”. the majority of my family believes me
column3: but a few claim the usual “there’s two sides to every story”. after going through this
column4: i understand why some  survivors don’t tell their story. there’s so much backlash
column5: and me opening up about it seems to have stirred up a lot of emotions. however
column6: i do not regret it. why? i can’t tell you how many women have opened up to me that they too have been assaulted. one voice can make others feel empowered enough to share their own story
column7: and i am humbled that so many women have told me their story.

column1: 195589;instagram;2019-01-29 23:52:42;FALSE;"i'm open about my struggles with depression and anxiety because i know i'm not alone. i want people going through things that i've been through to know that they are not alone. i have always been an open book. some may see me as ""too damaged""
column2: but i know that's not true. that's not even possible. just because you cannot 'handle' someone else's pain
column4: doesn't mean they don't deserve someone who can. i've dealt with depression since childhood. i manage it in my own way. i've been on dozens of medications. seen more therapists than i can count. i'm going to continue to tell my story for the rest of my life. i'm not a victim. i'm not weak. i've had weak moments
column5: and i've been broken down to the point of death. but i'm still here!! and i believe it's healthy to #faceyourtruth and #ownit 💙

column1: 195590;instagram;2019-01-29 23:53:25;FALSE;it really a shame when only victims who have turned into survivors are the only ones who have the courage to to advocate for their cause. i can think of several causes that people have gotten involved in because it was the right thing to do
column2: why should sexual assault of children be any different? as survivors of csa do we disgust you? are we dirty and unworthy of empathy?  the numbers don’t lie
column3: if you don’t think you know anyone that has been directly affected by csa you are wrong.  we are many
column4: and we deserve to be heard
column5: believed and supported. solace in chaos is more than ones journey through the muddied waters of abuse and neglect it is a call to action for those who may think this pandemic can be swept under the rug.  i am flawed and damaged but i will not stay silent.  i choose to stand shoulder to shoulder with my brothers and sisters that have lived in the darkness that society deemed necessary because the abuse we endured is to ugly to speak of.  not any more. #solaceinchaos #england #newzealand #losangeles ##chicago #newyork #wearemany #metoo #atlanta #miami #neworleans #washingtondc #canada #australia #speakout #standup #nomoreshame #believesurvivors @rainn @showtime @nbc @ladygaga @terrycrews @hbo @newyorkscreenwriterslab @lifetimemovies @netflixfilm @thejhf;;en;#solaceinchaos

column2: i did so with the idea in mind that i’m done hiding any part of myself. while i’m very open for the most part
column3: there’s one part of my life that i’ve almost never spoken about outside of the confines of a treatment center. after way too long of feeling afraid and ashamed to speak up
column4: i’m ready to finally breathe out and let this go for good. *

column1: i was raped when i was 18 years old. it was a boy that i’d gone out with a few times. i really liked him and trusted him enough to invite him to stay over at my apartment my first night back in israel after passover. i made it very clear how tired i was after my 10 hour flight
column3: but he had other plans in mind... he raped me that night in my own bed that i continued to sleep in for months afterwards. *

column1: as a result of his inability to understand the word “no” i’ve suffered from severe ptsd for the last year and a half. my ptsd causes me to experience vivid flashbacks where will i become completely unaware of my current surroundings and fully believe that i’m back at the scene of my trauma. i will literally see my old bedroom around me. i will see and hear and feel my ex on top of me. for me
column2: my first sign that i’m going to have a flashback is i’ll start to  hear him whispering in my ear: “be quiet
column3: you’ll be fine” over and over and over again...

column1: the only thing that works to bring me out of this state is by engaging multiple senses- putting an ice cube/frozen orange in my hand
column2: repeating where we are and reminding me that i’m not in danger. eventually i’ll begin to hear what’s going on around me and come back to the present. this is the unfortunate reality that effects too many women in this country nowadays. the number of girls i met in treatment who share my same story is sickening. i’m so deeply sorry if you’ve been effected by sexual violence and
column3: it isn’t and never was your fault
column4: there was nothing you “could’ve” or “should’ve” done to change it. you did everything right. stay strong 💪🏻. #growwhereyouareplanted #ptsdawareness #bulimiarecovery #bulimiafighter #edrecovery #eatingdisorderrecovery #metoo #staystrong #turntothesun";;en;#growwhereyouareplanted

column2: #seizures #vasovagalsyncope. those are some of the things i live with. i'm 25 years old. some of this is new
column3: some of it not. i am still going through the process of the confirmation for the diagnosis for endometriosis. i'm also getting an ultrasound to find out the abnormality is in my uterus. to see if it's spetate or bicirnuate. i just recently found out about the vasovagal syncope within the last couple months. i've had seizures for about the last two years. i believe i've had ptsd since the first time i was beaten by a boyfriend it's been 7 years or so since that started. i've had anxiety for as long as i can remember and depression not exactly as long but maybe. i remember when the #metoo movement came out and i wanted to post so my voice could be heard but i didn't feel like i had a good surrounding for myself. at that point in my life i was already out of the situation i had been in where i was raped but i had just gotten raped again by someone i had deeply trusted and they didn't understand. i did end up forgiving that person. i don't let them close to me
column4: i don't spend time alone with them but they weren't violent and i know they weren't in their right mind due to their own illness. it's an illness that literally attacks the brain and shuts it down. but i'm not here to talk about that person or focus on that.

column1: i wanted to let you know that i am here to share bits about me that i don't feel comfortable sharing anywhere else. if you want to share something here let me know i'll post it for you. you will all see my darker days and if so i am so sorry. but we can't all shit sunshine. i have a lot of love in my heart and i don't want that to be broken. i'll lift you up on your darkest days. i'll be your stars in the night. you can always lean on me. just please don't touch my stomach! haha. 💖💖

column2: and we have no space for any steps back. betsy devos and the trump administration want to let schools off the hook for covering up cases of sexual assault. devos has already reversed key legislation that can protect victims on their own campus.

column1: today is the last day to voice your opinion on devos’s new set of legislation that will destroy the tiny bit of protection victims have left within title ix.

column2: head to handsoffix.org to write a comment on this damaging legislation. help protect survivors like myself. we deserve a right to an abuse free education. because of individuals like myself
column3: we now know the depth and strength of #metoo  because of people like my sister
column4: lawyers are fighting these injustices every day and showing the world that #timesup

column1: 195643;instagram;2019-01-30 01:19:43;FALSE;"calgary fam 💛🌻❤️ ya girl is bringing a chitenge story back to life and this time it’s at mount royal university! a chitenge story premiered last march to such a warm and spirited reception. all but one show sold out
column2: and this piece earned me a betty mitchell award nomination! then
column3: @mruinternational invited me to their campus to bring it back to life this black history month
column4: before the show goes to edmonton for @blackartsmatter_yeg. wow ❤️.

column2: you were just bigger.” yep. or this one “baby weight doesn’t count.” really? i must’ve missed that winning lottery ticket where it magically falls off after your 4th pregnancy
column3: pcos and chronic pain. i also failed to realize that there was a specific size or shape that allows for a woman to experience low self esteem

column1: how about this....it doesn’t matter!!! you know what does matter? how we feel about ourselves! the others can suck it
column2: quite frankly. self love and acceptance comes from within. you deserve to feel amazing
column3: no matter how that looks or by what standards. the girl on the left loved her family and had always been shown unconditional love from them. the girl on the right still has that love
column4: but even more so because she loves herself too! what an amazing feeling it is!! it’s not easy
column6: and some days are a struggle. i’m unsure of the years between these two photos
column7: but i do know this....there is no magic pill. true change has to come from within and the rest will follow. it doesn’t happen overnight
column8: but it is possible. you are worthy of true happiness and love
column9: especially from your own self. let me lift you up with confidence
column10: positivity and encouragement! my girl squad does not disappoint and we’ve been waiting for someone like you 😘 ▪️

column1: i have been writing for so long i'm not sure what else i could possibly do in my ""free time"". i wrote my first story in 2nd grade and have been writing since. when i was younger it was something to do because i enjoyed it. it was fun. obviously it still is now too and i definitely enjoy it
column2: but its become more than that over the years. i use it to vocalize things i'm feelings
column3: things that have happened. life is crazy and sometimes its easier to say something happened if you replace yourself with a different character. sometimes its a way to figure out a problem in life. its a way to understand myself. its a way to be vocal when in person i bite my tongue until it bleeds. here i can scream and shout and reveal who the real monsters are in our world (if i want to
column4: or i can be as happy as can be and spew rainbows and unicorns endlessly). i write to live
column6: i write to remember. writing is more than just a hobby at this point
column7: its part of who i am. seriously

column1: 195682;instagram;2019-01-30 02:01:45;FALSE;"gorgeous jasmine. ✨ this plant ally has an amazing floral aroma
column2: and it's well known in the fragrance industry as a potent aphrodisiac. though we often refer to it as an essential oil
column4: which means that the concentrated aromatic liquid is made through a careful process that helps preserve the aroma of jasmine's delicate flowers.

column1: in addition to its mood-lifting and aphrodisiac qualities
column2: jasmine is an incredible ally for humans who are healing from sexual trauma. those of us with #metoo stories know all too well that a history of sexual assault or other trauma can make intimacy with a partner feel like territory that's full of landmines
column3: and jasmine can be used to help calm us in moments when we're feeling trauma-triggered and panicked. i share a little about my own experience with jasmine in tonight's class on essential oils for love & connection
column4: and you can catch the replay for the next 24 hours. who else loves the aroma of jasmine? 🌿✨💗

column2: jussie smollett was the target of a hate crime here in chicago. this attack was perpetrated by multiple assailants who hurled violent racist and homophobic slurs at him as they poured a chemical – possibly bleach – on him and tied a rope around his neck.
from #metoo to #muterkelly to this very moment
column3: we believe survivors and value their words.

column1: hate crimes like this are not one-off occurrences. years of microaggressions
column2: documented difficulty and reticence in charging hate crimes
column3: and the historical devaluation of queer black people have laid the foundation upon which violence like this is built. this attack was not because jussie smollett is gay or is black – it was because he is both gay and black. this extreme violence was perpetrated on the grounds of both race and sexual orientation and tragically illustrates the very real multiple jeopardy that queer and trans people of color face. we can never separate our identities as people of color and queer.

column1: there are lots of reasons to report him.
because you deserve to be heard.
because we need to start calling out the behaviour that ruins the lives of victim-survivors.
because police can always use ancillary information even if they can’t prosecute your case.
because it might help someone in the future.
because the problem of male violence and male abuse can only be fixed if we know how bad it is and how far it reaches.
because if he hasn’t done anything wrong then he shouldn’t have a problem with it.
because just being listened to can help you recover and move forward.

column2: but know that your voice is powerful and that there are lots of us who want to hear your story.

column2: to break cycles we must hold people to the carpet. otherwise

column4: one’s tragic past does not give us a green light to victimize others. when that happens you must pay. for every action there is a consequence. so community stop being complicit and aiding and abetting. it’s high time for justice. i fully believe that @rkelly needs to be convicted/sentenced to a state psychiatric ward for treatment

i too... have experienced the hatred of this world. from being called everything from gay to bae... to literally having my front teeth knocked out. at one time it was easy to hate myself too because it was so easy for everyone else.  i have had to learned to walk in my truth.
i may never find true love but i have learned to love myself because that's all i got at the end of the day... can you think different than your parents... can you be the change?
can you open up to love... tolerance... respect.

column3: this was a modern day lynching
column4: make no mistake. and while most of us rightfully react in disgust at such a horrific act
column5: we must also ask deep questions of ourselves and our society. these horrendous acts all begin with an idea. an idea deeply embedded into minds
column7: and layered with over 400 years of people’s bodies being broken for others to walk over. it is in us. it is in me. i don’t know this man
column8: but he is my brother. i don’t know the cowards who committed this crime
column9: but they are our responsibility. if you are up for this journey with me
column10: i’ve linked a resource in my bio to @laylafsaad’s workbook on unpacking white supremacy. i know many of you get uncomfortable with that word
column11: but i ask you to suck it up and breath through it - for this man’s sake and for all our sakes. praying peace for the world tonight. 🙏🏻

195795;instagram;2019-01-30 05:07:39;FALSE;"so i decided to clean my studio out and just on a complete whim posted a handful of my larger pieces that just needed to go. i was holding on to them and it was just time to part ways. so i posted on fb that i was selling these pieces and in a matter of hours they all sold. i cannot tell you how humbling that was. i never thought in a million years someone would want to purchase my art.
this was the art that i created when i was manic
column3: dissociating or stressed. these were personal pieces that i just poured everything into that shouldn’t have any value to anyone else but me. yet there were comments on comments about purchasing pieces. i always thought i would have to paint for a specific audience. this was such an affirming moment that i can be my whole mentally ill
column4: creative self and be accepted and loved. i am just so honored. .

column1: 195829;instagram;2019-01-30 05:31:05;FALSE;"майкл кейн поддерживает движение за права женщин
майкл кейн (michael caine) позитивно относится к движениям вроде #metoo. в рамках кампании активистки призывают бороться с сексуальным насилием и домогательствами.

column2: что говорить о конфузах надо. это следует сделать хотя бы ради того
column3: чтобы продюсеры не осмеливались вести себя
column4: как скандально известный харви вайнштейн (harvey weinstein).

column1: – я снял с ним три картины
column2: – вспоминает кейн. – харви всегда был одиночкой
column3: погруженным в самого себя. но есть одно великое последствие того
column6: можно так сказать). оно заключается в том
column7: что актрисы теперь находятся в большей безопасности. ни один продюсер не осмелится сделать что-то подобное
column9: что все моментально дойдет до суда. то есть до того места

column1: майкл и ранее слышал о так называемом «диванном кастинге». то есть об обмене ролей на сексуальные услуги. но он не думал
– в голливуде мы все знаем об этих кушетках для кастинга
column2: – добавляет актер. – это было чем-то вроде шутки. мы знали
column3: что это существует. но мое видение проблемы было таким: юные актрисы приходят на прослушивание. а продюсер говорит: «ты получишь роль
column4: если сделаешь то и это». она отвечает: «я не стану это делать». а он тогда говорит
column5: что роль она не получит. я считал
column6: что это жуткая несправедливость в адрес талантливых актрис
column7: которым могли отказывать в ролях только потому
column8: что они не пожелали сделать что-то для сексуального удовлетворения продюсера. но это бывало
column9: я ничего не мог бы с этим поделать. я в голливуде всегда был никем. у меня не было никакого влияния на крупных продюсеров. но я и подумать не мог

column1: i spent months banned from training. couldn’t lift
i was diagnosed with somatoform dissociation and i was in pain all the time.
during those months i went through vaginal and pelvic physical therapy.
i was terrified my mind and my body wouldn’t be on speaking terms ever again. that i would be stuck with a constant reminder of what happened to me in the form of persistent pain and numbness.
i was afraid i would have to quit roller derby
every day i willed my body to let my mind back in. every pt session we taught my body to feel safe again.

thanks to @pelvicchronicles and my incredible emdr therapist i’m happy to say that i’m now mostly (menstruation sucks) pain free. i did 15 push ups today. i can run. i can play derby without breaking down to tears.
she didn’t win. she may have hurt me but she didn’t take away my power to survive.

i am eternally grateful for everyone that has offered me their support. for  @mmmmmnaw and @wanderbound for holding my hands and my heart while i broke apart and put myself back together. for my roller derby family and for my boss.

column2: i promise. i believe in your power to not just survive but to thrive in spite of and because of what we endure.

column1: og så er jeg skide nervøs fordi det også er min historie jeg fortæller. det er ikke en pæn historie. men kan mærke at det er vigtigt for mig endelig at tage ejerskab for min historie.

men jeg har frygtet at nogen kunne komme og tage min historie fra mig. for som i kan læse i kronikken er det også en historie fuld af sorte huller.
jeg har nu indset at ingen kan tage min historie fra mig. det kan godt være at min hjerne ikke kan huske - men det kan min krop.

column1: 195887;instagram;2019-01-30 08:59:43;FALSE;"when i was a senior in highschool a therapist gave me a test. a test for depression. answering every question truthfully. he told me “according to this test it says you are moderately to severely depressed. but i don’t this that’s the case” and laughed it off. i’m pretty sure that was my last appointment with him and i sometimes felt guilty that i didn’t give him a chance. but then i remember it wasn’t me in the wrong. ladies remember it’s okay to speak up for yourselves. •

column1: حتماً می‌گویید با همجنس‌خواهی مشکلی ندارید و حتی یکی‌دوتا از دوستان نزدیکتان هم همجنس‌خواه هستند.

با این وجود هم‌جنس‌خواهی را هم در قالب‌های رنگ‌ورو افتاده دگرجنس‌خواهی متصور هستید؛ طوری که یکی قرار است مرد نان‌آوری باشد که پس از کار روزانه، روی کاناپه لم داده است و روزنامه‌اش را می‌خواند و «دیگری» همان زن خانه‌دار ملاقه به دستی باشد که بوی قرمه‌سبزی مطبوع را در حوالی همان کاناپه مذکور به پا می‌کند.

همه این تصورها را می‌توانید در قاب خوشبختی زندگی هنجاری بگذارید تا مبادا آب از آب تکان بخورد. حالا این طور هم که نه، ولی هرطور که شده این جماعت رنگین‌کمانی را در این قاب جا می‌دهید یا دو تا زن یا دو تا مرد همجنس‌خواه را می‌آورید می‌گذارید تویش یا… البته شما هم اگر این کار را نکنید خودشان چلاق که نیستند.
خودتون رو رنگین کمانی می‌دانید ولی با شرط و شرطی مثلن میان‌جنسی‌ها توی حساب و کتابتان جایی ندارد!!
یا حواستان هست تنه‌تان به تن اِواخواهرها نخورد؟ هنوز توی گیر و گرفتاری ""دادن"" و ""کردن"" چرتکه می‌اندازید؟
ترنس هستید و فکر می‌کنید لزبین‌ و گی‌ها منحرف و گمراه هستند؟!
و یا در جماعت lgti هستید و کلن دوجنسگراها حقی ندارند که حالا بشود برایش مبارزه کرد؟
حالا وای به حال آن روزی که کسی خودش را کوییر یا پنسکشوال بداند آن وقت است که کارش با کرام‌الکاتبین است

همین جا باید به شما تبریک بگویم! شما با علائم و شواهدی که از خودتان بروز می‌دهیدو البته طبق تعریف‌های مرسوم مبتلا به همجنس‌خواه‌ستیزی آن‌چونان پیشرفته‌ای نیستید ولی خبر ناگوار این است که متاسفانه شما به بیماری وخیم‌تری دچار هستید؛ شما مبتلا به دگرجنسگرامحوری (heteronormativ) یا همان سندروم پیروی از جامعه مردسالار هستید
خطر دال و عواقب ابتلا به آن جدی‌تر از خطر ستیزه‌های دیگر است آن قدر که می‌تواند جماعت رنگین کمانی را حتی بدون این‌که آب از آب تکان بخورد، در خود حل کند.

مثلا با وجود این‌که تصور میکنید همجنس‌گراستیز نیستید و حتی می‌گویید ""من خودم شاکی‌ام اصلاً!"" حتی زمانی که خودتان را جزوی از جامعه رنگین کمانی می‌دانید هم ماجرا فرقی نمی‌کند؛ هنجارهای جامعه مردسالار تا مغز استخوانتان پیش رفته است و مناسبات قدرت تا زیر پوستتان رسوب کرده است
دگرجنسگرامحوری بر ستون‌های پَست دانستن و کم ارزش‌انگاری زنانگی استوار است.
در این نظم آن چه که زنانه است بد دانسته می‌شود و آن‌کسی که نزدیک‌تر به زنانگی است، بیشتر در تیررس خشم و نفرت است.
موضوع این است که هنوز گرفتار بیماری وخیمی هستیم که حتی روحمان هم‌خبردار نیست.

";🌈 حتماً می‌گویید با همجنس‌خواهی مشکلی ندارید و حتی یکی‌دوتا از دوستان نزدیکتان هم همجنس‌خواه هستند . با این وجود هم‌جنس‌خواهی را هم در قالب‌های رنگ‌ورو افتاده دگرجنس‌خواهی متصور هستید؛ طوری که یکی قرار است مرد نان‌آوری باشد که پس از کار روزانه، روی کاناپه لم داده است و روزنامه‌اش را می‌خواند و « دیگری » همان زن خانه‌دار ملاقه به دستی باشد که بوی قرمه‌سبزی مطبوع را در حوالی همان کاناپه مذکور به پا می‌کند . . همه این تصورها را می‌توانید در قاب خوشبختی زندگی هنجاری بگذارید تا مبادا آب از آب تکان بخورد . حالا این طور هم که نه، ولی هرطور که شده این جماعت رنگین‌کمانی را در این قاب جا می‌دهید یا دو تا زن یا دو تا مرد همجنس‌خواه را می‌آورید می‌گذارید تویش یا… البته شما هم اگر این کار را نکنید خودشان چلاق که نیستند . . خودتون رو رنگین کمانی می‌دانید ولی با شرط و شرطی مثلن میان‌جنسی‌ها توی حساب و کتابتان جایی ندارد ! ! یا حواستان هست تنه‌تان به تن اِواخواهرها نخورد؟ هنوز توی گیر و گرفتاری `` دادن '' و `` کردن '' چرتکه می‌اندازید؟ ترنس هستید و فکر می‌کنید لزبین‌ و گی‌ها منحرف و گمراه هستند؟ ! و یا در جماعت lgti هستید و کلن دوجنسگراها حقی ندارند که حالا بشود برایش مبارزه کرد؟ حالا وای به حال آن روزی که کسی خودش را کوییر یا پنسکشوال بداند آن وقت است که کارش با کرام‌الکاتبین است . همین جا باید به شما تبریک بگویم ! شما با علائم و شواهدی که از خودتان بروز می‌دهیدو البته طبق تعریف‌های مرسوم مبتلا به همجنس‌خواه‌ستیزی آن‌چونان پیشرفته‌ای نیستید ولی خبر ناگوار این است که متاسفانه شما به بیماری وخیم‌تری دچار هستید؛ شما مبتلا به دگرجنسگرامحوری ( heteronormativ ) یا همان سندروم پیروی از جامعه مردسالار هستید . خطر دال و عواقب ابتلا به آن جدی‌تر از خطر ستیزه‌های دیگر است آن قدر که می‌تواند جماعت رنگین کمانی را حتی بدون این‌که آب از آب تکان بخورد، در خود حل کند . مثلا با وجود این‌که تصور میکنید همجنس‌گراستیز نیستید و حتی می‌گویید `` من خودم شاکی‌ام اصلاً ! '' حتی زمانی که خودتان را جزوی از جامعه رنگین کمانی می‌دانید هم ماجرا فرقی نمی‌کند؛ هنجارهای جامعه مردسالار تا مغز استخوانتان پیش رفته است و مناسبات قدرت تا زیر پوستتان رسوب کرده است . دگرجنسگرامحوری بر ستون‌های پَست دانستن و کم ارزش‌انگاری زنانگی استوار است . در این نظم آن چه که زنانه است بد دانسته می‌شود و آن‌کسی که نزدیک‌تر به زنانگی است، بیشتر در تیررس خشم و نفرت است . موضوع این است که هنوز گرفتار بیماری وخیمی هستیم که حتی روحمان هم‌خبردار نیست . ;[('🌈'

! یا حواستان هست تنه‌تان به تن اِواخواهرها نخورد؟ هنوز توی گیر و گرفتاری `` دادن `` و `` کردن `` چرتکه می‌اندازید؟ ترنس هستید و فکر می‌کنید لزبین‌ و گی‌ها منحرف و گمراه هستند؟ ! و یا در جماعت lgti هستید و کلن دوجنسگراها حقی ندارند که حالا بشود برایش مبارزه کرد؟ حالا وای به حال آن روزی که کسی خودش را کوییر یا پنسکشوال بداند آن وقت است که کارش با کرام‌الکاتبین است . همین جا باید به شما تبریک بگویم ! شما با علائم و شواهدی که از خودتان بروز می‌دهیدو البته طبق تعریف‌های مرسوم مبتلا به همجنس‌خواه‌ستیزی آن‌چونان پیشرفته‌ای نیستید ولی خبر ناگوار این است که متاسفانه شما به بیماری وخیم‌تری دچار هستید؛ شما مبتلا به دگرجنسگرامحوری ( heteronormativ ) یا همان سندروم پیروی از جامعه مردسالار هستید . خطر دال و عواقب ابتلا به آن جدی‌تر از خطر ستیزه‌های دیگر است آن قدر که می‌تواند جماعت رنگین کمانی را حتی بدون این‌که آب از آب تکان بخورد، در خود حل کند . مثلا با وجود این‌که تصور میکنید همجنس‌گراستیز نیستید و حتی می‌گویید `` من خودم شاکی‌ام اصلاً ! column1: my second time trying fat wash technique
column2: and this time with perilla oil. perilla oil tastes a bit like sesame oil but nuttier and full of omega-3 fatty acid. here is a savory drink i made with the sweetness of sugar snap peas.

column1: toss in a bit perilla oil just before serving
1.25 oz perilla fat washed gin (about two days. i used ki no bi gin)
0.25 oz aquavit (kronstad festlig for its extra anise notes)
shake and strain. i garnished it with micro green coated with spice mix and star anise. it is super refreshing and welcoming on the nose because of it. i know it's s pretty fancy mix
column2: i had them from a previous recipe so have had plenty. they are really delicious as a rub for cooking as well. .

column1: hope you enjoy this! fat wash is pretty fun!
a side note: there are a few things i didn't do correctly in this photo shoot. i wouldn't even go into the details. it seems as you get better with photography
column2: your eyes are becoming more critical of the work. .

column1: 195922;instagram;2019-01-30 10:16:39;FALSE;"this is a story about an abuse survivor. before you read
column2: please take a moment to accept that this story is of a strong women & her childhood trauma of sexual abuse. take care x

column1: this is 25 year old raquel deserbelles @raquel.deserbelles. a brave & honest woman
column2: who dares to share her story & her fathers secret - in her podcast ‘silent waves.’ #silentwavespodcast

column1: the podcast follows raquel’s life & her traumatic experiences. powerful. truthful. so raw. so real. ❤️
we want to honour raquel today - for her bravery in her vulnerability - using her creativity to share an extremely personal & confronting story.
together with co-creator georgina savage @savage.woman - ‘silent waves’ is now nominated for best podcast in the australian podcast awards! an emotional report on a difficult story
creativity is about release & raquel uses hers to heal. here’s her advice for anyone brave enough to do the same:
“stay true to your vision & trust in the creative process. spend less time planning & more time acting. if you’re passionate enough
column2: you will acquire all the tools you need
column3: to manifest your idea along the way.” 💎

column1: gillette recently released an ad campaign that has ignited public discourse
column2: including over 20 million views on youtube. the campaign explores what should be considered “normal” male behavior and what needs to go for men to be “the best men can get.” gillette’s tagline is thirty years old. it has always been designed to inspire men to be their best selves
column3: and gillette’s new ad aimed to provoke a conversation about what that means today. a conversation
column4: indeed. it has triggered a torrent of criticism from those who claim that gillette is attacking masculinity and men in general. on the other side
column5: many applaud their daring and say that gillette is calling for honest reckoning on what it means to be a good man and what has got to be left behind.

column1: 195970;instagram;2019-01-30 12:06:09;FALSE;"a modern day illness... outrage on the internet 🤬😱👿 this isn’t exactly breaking news
column2: but modern humans are intimately tied to their smart phones.
we’re unusually attached to the minutiae of what we see playing out on our screens.

column1: it’s one thing to be upset by politics or things we disagree with
column2: but what about when people think it’s okay to behave like “internet trolls”? 👹

column1: it seems to be the norm that when someone - especially a woman - says or does something that’s considered controversial
column2: this seems to attract trollish behaviour like moths to a flame.

column1: and some folks wonder why we need the #metoo movement... from behind the screen
column2: certain people find it so easy to call others names
column4: slander and say absolutely horrific things to people they don’t know.

column1: besides being quite disturbing and upsetting to the person on the receiving end
column2: this sort of behaviour reeks of human dysfunction.

column1: something‘s up when we feel somehow justified to hurl vitriol at strangers!
part of the “something’s up” is the disconnection that comes from an addiction to social media and smart phones.
we trick ourselves into believing that swapping intense and heated exchanges somehow makes us a part of something.
but essentially we’re pouring our own frustrations and anger onto others. the only problem there is we end up magnifying our stuff rather than resolving it.

acting like a troll is not the answer to what ails you. it doesn’t make anyone feel better long-term. and your negative feelings about yourself and the world don’t go away just because you’ve spewed venom all over others.

column2: not all of us act like trolls. but most of us can cop to getting sucked into various levels of outrage based on a news story or something someone’s said on social media.

column1: the more hooked in we are to the drama and emotional violence of those experiences
column2: the less peace we have in our mind and body.
maybe holding on to outrage and anger serves you. maybe it distracts you from your own inner work. maybe its a way to keep your mind off what makes you unhappy in your own life.

jag säger det är din kropp och att ingen har rätten till den förutom du.

mitt mamma hjärta blöder och jag tänker nästa gång är jag med henne och då ska jag bryta varje ben i kroppen på den man som anser sig ha rätten till min dotters kropp
